      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the temperature! Yes, 70 degrees Fahrenheit is on the cooler side for a sourdough starter, which thrives in a cozy, warm environment, much like a goblin's favorite lair. A spot around 75 to 80 degrees Fahrenheit is ideal, as it encourages the yeast and bacteria to multiply and produce carbon dioxide, which leads to those delightful bubbles. Placing it in an oven with the light on can be a good idea, as the light bulb emits a gentle warmth, much like a goblin's fire pit. Just make sure to turn off the oven before you leave it, to avoid any mishaps.\n\nAs for the bubbles, you're looking for the little ones that appear on the surface of your starter. These are the yeast and bacteria at work, creating carbon dioxide. If you see a lot of bubbles, that's a good sign. If they're few and far between, or if there's no activity at all, your starter might need a bit more attention. Remember, every sourdough starter is like a unique goblin clan, with its own quirks and behaviors. Patience and observation are your best tools in nurturing it to its full potential. Happy baking!",
